diskrete
Smack-Fu Master, in training
Registered: Sep 15, 2009Posts: 43
Posted: Thu Apr 18, 2013 2:28 pm
mattclary wrote:Quote:It's worth noting, however, that Earth sits right on the inner edge of this boundaryIf I interpret this statement correctly, we are "on the warm side" of habitable? Seems like a stretch considering how much time the globe spends in ice ages. I would not want us to be much farther from the sun.The inner boundary is generally agreed to be at 0.95 AU. Earth, of course, is at 1.0 AU. The outer boundary depends on your definition and estimates range from 1.15 AU to 1.4 AU.Recent research (http://physicsworld.com/cws/article/new ... table-zone) shows the inner edge may be even closer, at 0.99 AU. That would mean if we were 1% closer to the Sun, Earth would not be habitable.
